This image illustrates a three-stage pipeline for identifying and fixing accessibility gaps in videos to support users with visual or hearing impairments.

*   **A. Identify Accessibility Issues:** The system first segments the audio and video tracks separately [ref: Identify Accessibility Issues]. It then aligns these segments to identify "mismatches" or gaps where the visual content is not described by the audio (indicated by low matching scores like 0.4) or where important sounds like music are not captioned [ref: Match Audio & Video].
*   **B. Address Accessibility Issues:** A specialized editing interface allows users to fill these gaps [ref: Address Accessibility Issues]. The interface highlights specific time segments in the audio and visual tracks that require attention, providing text boxes to author new captions and video descriptions [ref: Editor Interface].
*   **C. Play Accessible Video:** The final output is an accessible video player [ref: Play Accessible Video]. It displays closed captions for dialogue and sounds (e.g., "This step makes removing the cheesecake a breeze") and provides audio descriptions for visual actions that were previously silent (e.g., "She lines the pan with foil") [ref: Final Accessible Output].

This screenshot illustrates an authoring interface designed to help users create accessible video content by adding captions and audio descriptions. [ref: Interface Overview]

The labeled components include:

*   **(A) Issue Counter:** Displays the remaining "audio issues" and "visual issues" identified by the system that require user attention. [ref: Accessibility Dashboard]
*   **(B) Video Player:** An embedded player that allows the author to review the video while editing. [ref: Video Playback]
*   **(C) Track Timelines:** Visual representations of the audio and visual tracks, where colored blocks indicate segments that may need descriptions or captions. [ref: Timeline Visualization]
*   **(D) Captions Preview:** Shows how the captions will appear to the end user in real-time. [ref: Preview Pane]
*   **(E) Captions Column:** A dedicated space to transcribe speech or "Describe the sound" for segments requiring non-speech audio information. [ref: Captioning Interface]
*   **(F) Video Description Column:** An area for authors to "Describe the visual" elements, which are later used for audio description for blind or low-vision viewers. [ref: Description Interface]
*   **(G) Importance Slider:** A control (set to "Top 35%" here) likely used to filter or prioritize which segments the system suggests describing based on an importance threshold. [ref: Selection Controls]
*   **(H) Entry Management:** Save and edit buttons for individual text entries, allowing the user to commit their changes to specific timestamps. [ref: Entry Controls]
